== Market ==

In 2012 the C919 order book stood at 380 units worth US$26 billion,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Yu Dawei and Liang Dongmei |date=18 December 2012 |title=Comac C919 Airliner Project Flying in the Dark |url=http://www.chinaaviationdaily.com/news/23/23020.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929221734/http://www.chinaaviationdaily.com/news/23/23020.html |archive-date=29 September 2018 |access-date=5 May 2017 |website=[[Caixin]] Online |publisher=China Aviation Daily}}</ref> and averaging ${{#expr:26000/380round1}} million per unit. [[FlightGlobal]]'s Ascend market values in 2013 were $49.2 million for the [[Airbus A320neo]], {{#expr:(100.2-49.2)/100.2*100round0}}% less than its $100.2 million [[list price]] and $51.4 million for the [[Boeing 737 MAX]]-8, {{#expr:(100.5-51.4)/100.5*100round0}}% less than its $100.5 million list price.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Vincent Lamigeon |date=13 June 2013 |title=Le vrai prix des avions d'Airbus et de Boeing |url=http://www.challenges.fr/salon-du-bourget-2013/20130612.CHA0743/le-vrai-prix-des-avions-d-airbus-et-de-boeing.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409070546/http://www.challenges.fr/salon-du-bourget-2013/20130612.CHA0743/le-vrai-prix-des-avions-d-airbus-et-de-boeing.html |archive-date=9 April 2015 |publisher=Challenges.fr |language=fr}}</ref>

The Chinese airlines that have placed orders for the C919 already have either the [[Boeing 737]] or [[Airbus A320]] in their fleets.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 May 2012 |title=COMAC C919, against Airbus and Boeing duopoly |url=http://airlineberg.com/2012/05/19/airlineberg-analysis-comac-c919-against-airbus-and-boeing-duopoly/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112105352/http://airlineberg.com/2012/05/19/airlineberg-analysis-comac-c919-against-airbus-and-boeing-duopoly/ |archive-date=12 November 2012 |website=Airlineberg}}</ref> In 2013, Chinese state-owned newspaper ''[[Global Times]]'' complained that an ''[[Aviation Week]]'' editorial about the bleak prospects for the aircraft "maliciously disparaged the future outlook for the C919".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Joe Anselmo |date=18 July 2013 |title=China Newspaper Slams Aviation Week For 'Oppressive Scheme |url=http://aviationweek.com/blog/china-newspaper-slams-aviation-week-oppressive-scheme |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025134927/http://aviationweek.com/blog/china-newspaper-slams-aviation-week-oppressive-scheme |archive-date=25 October 2016 |access-date=5 May 2017 |website=Aviation Week}}</ref>

COMAC aims to take a fifth of the global [[narrowbody]] market and a third of the Chinese market by 2035.<ref name="ATW170505" /> It expects 2,000 sales until 2037.<ref>{{Cite news |date=5 May 2017 |title=What C919 means to China jet industry and domestic airlines |work=EJ Insight |url=http://www.ejinsight.com/20170505-what-c919-means-to-china-jet-industry-and-domestic-airlines/ |url-status=live |access-date=6 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505120353/http://www.ejinsight.com/20170505-what-c919-means-to-china-jet-industry-and-domestic-airlines/ |archive-date=5 May 2017}}</ref> The ''[[Financial Times]]'' commented that China considers the success of the plane a source of national pride.<ref>{{Cite news |date=29 April 2017 |title=China's challenger to Airbus and Boeing set for skies at last |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/71d7fed8-2bf2-11e7-9ec8-168383da43b7 |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |access-date=6 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501141134/https://www.ft.com/content/71d7fed8-2bf2-11e7-9ec8-168383da43b7 |archive-date=1 May 2017}}.</ref>

The newspaper also claimed in 2017 that the C919 was outdated by 10–15 years compared to the Airbus A320neo and Boeing 737 MAX 8, and would probably cost more to operate.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ben Bland |date=17 May 2017 |title=Chinese aviation finally takes off with help from the west |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/b7f26c06-349d-11e7-99bd-13beb0903fa3 |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |access-date=27 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710131040/https://www.ft.com/content/b7f26c06-349d-11e7-99bd-13beb0903fa3 |archive-date=10 July 2017}}</ref>
Its range of {{cvt|2,200–3,000|nmi}} fell short of the {{cvt|3,400 and 3,550|nmi}} of the A320neo and the 737 MAX 8; the C919 [[payload-range]] and economics were similar to the current single-aisles, but would not be able to compete with the Neo and Max.<!--<ref name="Flight26oct2018" />-->

In 2018, [[FlightGlobal]] forecast a total of 1,209 deliveries: 687 standard and 522 stretched variants, 85% of these in China.<ref name="Flight26oct2018" /> As of December 2024, all 16 operational C919 had carried more than one million revenue passengers.<ref>{{Cite web |title=COMAC to Significantly Increase Production of C919 in 2025 – International Federation of Airworthiness. |url=https://ifairworthy.com/comac-to-significantly-increase-production-of-c919-in-2025/ |access-date=2025-02-16 |language=en-GB}}</ref>

The 125% duty imposed by China in April 2025 on American imports to China, in retaliation for US President Trump's tariff hikes,  significantly raised the cost of [[Boeing 737 MAX|Boeing jets]] being sold to Chinese airlines. Due to this financial burden, analysts believed that Chinese airlines might begin to lean stronger towards domestic alternatives like [[Comac|COMAC]], or towards [[Airbus A320neo family|Airbus]] planes.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-04-15 |title=China orders carriers to suspend Boeing jet deliveries amid trade war, Bloomberg News reports |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/aerospace-defense/china-orders-halts-boeing-jet-deliveries-bloomberg-news-reports-2025-04-15/ |access-date=2025-04-15 |website=Reuters}}</ref> In May 2025, [[Ryanair]] CEO [[Michael O'Leary (businessman)|Michael O'Leary]] said his airline might consider acquiring COMAC planes in lieu of their planned 737 MAX orders if the tariffs led to an increase in the price of Boeing planes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ryanair could stop buying Boeing if Trump tariffs bite, CEO warns |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/ryanair-could-stop-buying-boeing-if-trump-tariffs-bite-ceo-warns/ |access-date=1 May 2025 |work=POLITICO |date=1 May 2025}}</ref> In response, US lawmaker [[Raja Krishnamoorthi]] of the [[United States House Select Committee on Strategic Competition between the United States and the Chinese Communist Party|House Select Committee on the CCP]] asked O'Leary to retract his statements due to security concerns.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Shepardson |first1=David |last2=Lampert |first2=Allison |date=2025-05-01 |title=US lawmaker warns Ryanair against buying Chinese-made planes |url=https://www.reuters.com/sustainability/boards-policy-regulation/us-lawmaker-warns-ryanair-against-buying-chinese-made-planes-2025-04-30/ |access-date=2025-09-21 |work=Reuters |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=29 April 2025 |title=Letter to Ryanair regarding COMAC |url=https://democrats-selectcommitteeontheccp.house.gov/sites/evo-subsites/democrats-selectcommitteeontheccp.house.gov/files/evo-media-document/4.29.25_letter-to-ryanair-re-comac.pdf}}</ref>

